  "text": "By contrast, we hypothesised a distinct profile of results for recalling very recent scene memories that had been formed just 30 min before scanning. As these had not yet undergone systems consolidation, we expected less demand on the process of scene construction, and thus reduced hippocampus activation. Note that this is the opposite viewpoint to standard systems consolidation theory, which states that memories become more independent of the hippocampus over time [CITATION_1] . In common with the constructing novel scenes and recalling scenes from a week earlier, the 30-min recall task required subjects to produce simulated sensory experience, and we expected this to be reflected by engagement of PHC and RSC.",
